{"id":"1907.09437","submitter":"Alexander Roberts","authors":"Micha{\\l} Przykucki, Alexander Roberts, Alex Scott","title":"Parking on the integers","comments":"28 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Models of parking in which cars are placed randomly and then move according\nto a deterministic rule have been studied since the work of Konheim and Weiss\nin the 1960s. Recently, Damron, Gravner, Junge, Lyu, and Sivakoff introduced a\nmodel in which cars are both placed and move at random. Independently at each\npoint of a Cayley graph $G$, we place a car with probability $p$, and otherwise\nan empty parking space. Each car independently executes a random walk until it\nfinds an empty space in which to park. In this paper we introduce three new\ntechniques for studying the model, namely the space-based parking model, and\nthe strategies for parking and for car removal. These allow us to study the\noriginal model by coupling it with models where parking behaviour is easier to\ncontrol. Applying our methods to the one-dimensional parking problem in\n$\\mathbb{Z}$, we improve on previous work, showing that for $p<1/2$ the\nexpected journey length of a car is finite, and for $p=1/2$ the expected\njourney length by time $t$ grows like $t^{3/4}$ up to a polylogarithmic factor.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 22 Jul 2019 17:21:31 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 18 Aug 2021 10:43:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-08-19"}
