{"id":"1907.09542","submitter":"Luca Buoninfante","authors":"Luca Buoninfante, Gaetano Lambiase, Antonio Stabile","title":"Testing fundamental physics with photon frequency shift","comments":"7 pages, 2 figures, 1 table. Version accepted for publication in EPJC\n  Letters","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1140/epjc/s10052-020-7712-5","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc astro-ph.EP astro-ph.SR hep-th quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We propose a high precision satellite experiment to further test Einstein's\nGeneral Relativity and constrain extended theories of gravity. We consider the\nfrequency shift of a photon radially exchanged between two observers located on\nEarth and on a satellite in circular orbit in the equatorial plane. In General\nRelativity there exists a peculiar satellite-distance at which the static\ncontribution to the frequency shift vanishes since the effects induced by pure\ngravity and special relativity compensate, while it can be non-zero in modified\ngravities, like in models with screening mechanisms. As an experimental device\nplaced on the satellite we choose a system of hydrogen atoms which can exhibit\nthe $1$s spin-flip transition from the singlet (unaligned proton-electron\nspins) to the triplet (aligned proton-electron spins) state induced by the\nabsorption of photons at $21.1$cm. The observation of an excited state would\nindicate that the frequency of the emitted and absorbed photon remains\nunchanged according to General Relativity. On the contrary, a non-zero\nfrequency shift, as predicted in extended theories of gravity, would prevent\nthe spin-flip transition and the hydrogen atoms from jumping into the excited\nstate. Such a detection would signify a smoking-gun signature of new physics\nbeyond special and general relativity.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 22 Jul 2019 19:31:24 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 15 Feb 2020 01:27:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"20